SIMPLE: occasion
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Occasion
<hw>Oc*ca"sion</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧k*k⟦amac⟧"zh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>occasion</ets>, L. <ets>occasio</ets>, fr.
<ets>occidere</ets>, <ets>occasum</ets>, to fall down; <ets>ob</ets>
(see <er>Ob-</er>) + <ets>cadere</ets> to fall. See <er>Chance</er>, and
cf. <er>Occident</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A falling out, happening,
or coming to pass; hence, that which falls out or happens; occurrence;
incident; event.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unlooked-for incidents of family history, and its hidden
excitements, and its arduous <qex>occasions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A favorable opportunity; a convenient or timely
chance; convenience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sin, taking <qex>occasion</qex> by the commandment, deceived
me.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. vii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll take the <qex>occasion</qex> which he gives to bring⟦br⟧
Him to his death.</q> <rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An occurrence or condition of affairs which brings
with it some unlooked-for event; that which incidentally brings to pass
an event, without being its efficient cause or sufficient reason;
accidental or incidental cause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her beauty was the <qex>occasion</qex> of the war.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Need; exigency; requirement; necessity; <as>as, I
have no <ex>occasion</ex> for firearms</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After we have served ourselves and our own
<qex>occasions</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When my <qex>occasions</qex> took me into France.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A reason or excuse; a motive; a
persuasion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose manner was, all passengers to stay,⟦br⟧
And entertain with her <qex>occasions</qex> sly.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>On occasion</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>in case of need;
in necessity; as convenience requires.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧That we might have
intelligence from him <xex>on occasion</xex>,⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>De
Foe.</au></rj> -- <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>occasionally; from time to time; now
and then.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Need; incident; use. See
<er>Opportunity</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Occasion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Occasion
<hw>Oc*ca"sion</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧k*k⟦amac⟧"zh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Occasioned</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ocr⟧k*k⟦amac⟧"zh⟦ucr⟧nd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Occasioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>occasionner</ets>.]</ety> <def>To give occasion to; to cause; to
produce; to induce; <as>as, to <ex>occasion</ex> anxiety</as>.</def>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If we inquire what it is that <qex>occasions</qex> men to make
several combinations of simple ideas into distinct modes.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Occasionable</ent>⟦br⟧
